    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_372204305" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/372204305" />
    <a title="David" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/11077996-david"><img alt="David" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1524363330p2/11077996.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/372204305?book_show_action=true">Jul 19, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="David" class="user" itemprop="url" name="David" href="/user/show/11077996-david">David</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer372204305" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14325272642479507654">Baffling and disappointing. The story seemed to be setting up beautifully for nothing but pure gold early on. The problems emerge when the reader senses the majority of the story&apos;s weight is squarely placed on the shoulders of a protagonist who is woefully misguided in virtually all of his views and interactions with others. Goldmund can do no wrong. He is great at everything. Everyone loves him. He is a wanderer (self-inflicted, no one forced him onto the aimless road to nowhere) who is acutely</span>
  <span id="freeText14325272642479507654" style="display:none">Baffling and disappointing. The story seemed to be setting up beautifully for nothing but pure gold early on. The problems emerge when the reader senses the majority of the story's weight is squarely placed on the shoulders of a protagonist who is woefully misguided in virtually all of his views and interactions with others. Goldmund can do no wrong. He is great at everything. Everyone loves him. He is a wanderer (self-inflicted, no one forced him onto the aimless road to nowhere) who is acutely aware of his sufferings (again, self-inflicted). He struggles on the road from one village to the next and simply bats his eyelashes or looks dreamily at a girl...and just like that, he has food and a place to sleep for the night. Apparently, he finds out later he is an art prodigy too. He never really expresses true gratitude to anyone for any of the copious number of unmerited favors he receives from strangers. But the focus keeps redirecting to his (self-inflicted!) sufferings. This is a massive disconnect which plagues the whole plot.<br /><br />This type of protagonist is suitable only for daydreams, not novels. If the reader feels that there no possibility of failure for the protagonist then his experiences are emptied of meaning. The novel quickly develops into a long string of events during which Goldmund enjoys the fruits of nature and of honest hard working people, and yet he can still somehow complain about how rotten the world and humanity are. One of his especially warped reflections arises out of his observations of a humble husband and wife running a fish market. He calls these people pigs for killing these beautiful fish all the while forgetting that people like these who make an honest living were the very ones who kept him from starving to death many times throughout the book. <br /><br />The most frustrating part was that I saw what Hesse was trying to do and liked the idea. In exploring the conflicts between polar phases of human nature, he was delving into an ancient but still fertile ground for reflection. The protagonist, however, could not hold it together. He was intended to be the core around which everything revolved and found its support, but he instead developed into an entirely unrealistic and tiresome distraction. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14325272642479507654" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


